<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="854" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d854">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/12691.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Brazilian Minister</gloss> to Mexico.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-01">
                                    <hi rend="italic">August 1, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>190. A telegram from our Consul at Saltillo calls attention to the
                            difference which the Constitutionalists make between an armistice and
                            the suspension of military operations. General Carranza’s Secretary for
                            Foreign Affairs, Fabela, informs him that when Provisional President
                            Carbajal’s envoys arrive with proper credentials and authority, military
                            operations will be suspended as announced.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>